Graeve;-;ARMA 3 is a great game but it is not for everyone. + Beautiful Visuals that stay in the realm of the realistic: Alot of games that have been released lately are quite beautiful but many of the visuals in these games are overdone and embellished ARMA manages to retain it's beauty while never really going over the edge into unrealistic. +Gameplay Depth: If you've always wanted to experience real lifelike military combat then ARMA is for you, combat in this game is slow, tactile, and unforgiving if you go into combat with a "Call of Duty" "Rambo" one man army mentality you will die. It is complex to the point of near ridiculousness with the game using nearly every key on the keyboard for keybinds, real physics, wind mapping, realistic scope alignment and several other things that bring the game as close to real combat as most people would ever want to be. + Map size: If you have never played an ARMA game before then you're in for something special, this game boasts the biggest map of any game I think I've ever played coming in just shy of being twice the size of Washington D.C.. + Steam Workshop: The game has full Workshop support with everything from new character models to new missions I haven't seen many guns or vehicles but I'm sure they'll come with time. - Accessibility: As I said at the beginning of this review this game is by no means for everyone the amount of content is staggering for a new player and getting used to the controls can be a nightmare if you're not dedicated to the process. - Limited community: As with every game there are good people and bad people in the community, you will find several people that are willing to help you learn the game and you will find alot of people willing to have patience with you but with that being said ARMA has a really dedicated and hardcore fanbase/community. You will get on servers where no one is going to help you, you will get on servers where no one is going to pay any attention to you, and you will get on servers where you are going to be yelled at/shot at for not doing your part there are communities in this game that use real military tactics have a full chain of command and have real military training. - Performance: This game is NOT easy to run I play on an Intel i7 4.5Ghz and an EVGA GTX670 4GB model and I have trouble maxing the game out in SINGLE PLAYER, in multiplayer you'll find yourself turning nearly everything to low just to squeeze every bit of performance out of your system that you can if you are not running top of the line tech I do not suggest playing this game you may end up disappointed. - You make your own fun: If you are not familiar with ARMA then you need to read up a little before your purchase, this game does not have a full campaign (Yet) and offers very little gameplay outside of multiplayer, while the game does have and extensive scenario creator if you are not familiar with how to use this feature the game is going to seem completely barren in terms of gameplay it is very much so a bare bones package if you don't understand how to make scenarios HOWEVER if you teach yourself how to do this the possibilities are virtually limitless. - Quite offputting to new players: I remember my first few days of playing ARMA II and I remember fairly vividly how much I hated them, trying to take the game in is alot for a person who has been used to playing typical games all their life if you put alot of time into the game you'll find enjoyment but it's a bit of a rocky road at first. Overall ARMA III is a great game that I personally LOVE but I can't speak for everyone, some will love this game and some will absolutely hate it, it IS a great game if you can manage to get past the steep learning curve. When considering purchasing this game keep in mind that alot of people that give it bad reviews probably don't play games like this very often this is not Battlefield and nor is it Call of Duty and that's okay it is it's own genre and deserves to be treated as such. 7.9/10
Sniperhunter;-;Shooting is as fun and precise as ever, and alongside the abundance of gigantic explosions, vehicle missions and intense firefights, it feels like the closest thing most of us will ever get to starring in an action film. In that sense, ArmA III is the classic Call of Duty formula at its best, with an important, defining difference: The emphasis on drone warfare, the exotic-but-grounded weaponry and the attention to detail in the believably high-tech signage and architecture makes ArmA III feel strikingly plausible even when it strays into non-historical settings. A number of other smaller design tweaks highlight the clever design of class creation in ArmA III. For instance perks now only affect your character, leaving it to the attachments system to affect your weapon. Thus if you want to do something like fast reload, which will make longtime players look for the Sleight of Hand perk, youll need to hook up your weapon with a fast clip attachment. The Kill Streak system has also been wisely replaced by Score Streaks, making every match less about how many kills and in what consecutive order you get them in, and more about doing whatever nets you the highest score. This accomplishes a majorly important feat: it makes every game less about your Kill / Death ratio. Sure, it still wont keep people from obsessing over it, but if you want to get it higher youre going to need to help with objectives. ArmA IIIs Zombies mode is the deepest the franchise has seen, even if its campaign narrative is reliant on the self-imposed stories arising from your roaming, zombie-slaughtering adventures with pals. The team at BI could have played it safe and ArmA III would have sold well, but instead they challenged assumptions and pushed the series forward in awesome new directions. Itll be hard to return to a campaign where I dont have the ability to shape it, and I simply cant imagine going back to the old loadout system now that Pick 10 exists. Combined with the host of subtle and overt improvements to the array of other systems, the additions to make it more appealing to Esports, and the more fleshed out Zombies mode, this is not just a fantastic Call of Duty game, but one of the best shooters of the last decade. 9.3 Amasing
