Reu;-;If you have played Operation Flashpoint (2001), you'll be right at home with this one - which is my biggest complaint about this game. Not much has changed in game mechanics since Flashpoint. The game is still pretty much waypoint oriented and even the editor is pretty much the same; meaning for instance setting up custom loadouts needs lots of scripting. The AI is downright horrible at times and actions that worked fine in previous releases (like driving in a convoy) are now nearly impossible, with lots of collisions and vehicles getting stuck. At least the first part of the single player campaign was a disappointment, with most of the action being 4vs4 infantry combat. Multiplayer and community made mods are what make this game, so if you enjoy huge realistic operations with real people, or having fun with mods in a beautiful sandbox - then this game might be for you. All in all, ARMA 3 is still in development and hopefully it will break free from the old Flashpoint mold. New features like graphical interfaces in the editor and flexibility to AI behaviour beyond the waypoint-system would be most welcome. Modifications add a lot of potential and replay value. Get ARMA 3 if you enjoy your games as projects. 3,5/5
Saladin;-;Great game, But it really depends who you are playing with that makes or breaks the game !
Izoul;-;Short and skinny: Don't buy this if you are looking for an alternative to the "Big 2" AKA: COD/BF series. It has never been that, and never will be. This is mistake #1 with this series/style of sim/game. People say "How is it compared to BF/COD?" It's the dead wrong question to ask. Preface/General: Now that aside, this is a simulator for it to be 'what you want it to be'. Think again more of a brutal sandbox mode game for either single or multiplayer. It doesn't hold hands, there is not much for a indication on how you die...you just die. Now keep in mind, you might travel from 5min to 30min, or even more to a target area in a sandbox like this without even seeing an enemy/pulling the trigger, and things can be 'randonized'....and if you screw up, or even if you do things perfect/to the book, you still might 'insta die' because you were in the wrong place/wrong time...much like real war. That's brutal to a lot of people who in turn ask the question of "Where is the fun in that?!" To that, I'd say "It's what you make of the experience, what you feel if you do acomplish someting in it." Performance: My experiences have always been that this sim always runs incredibly better for 'single player performance' for it's built in missions, or user generated download missions/etc. There are infinite downloads for user generated content, or you can easily make your own 'what if' missions. Again, you need to think 'hardcore BIG sandbox'. Multiplayer: Can be very fun, but user beware it's not for the faint of heart. If you are looking for a instant 'run and gun' like the intro mentioned titles, you are going to hate the expereince. It's not that at all. The community is more 'niche' and if you don't care for that, this is not your game/sim. Also, mutiplayer is way more taxing on your system for performance generally speaking depending on the mission/group size. Your mileage may vary. It does also support Track IR5 for those flight sim folks wanting that for your infantry control as well which is almost a must for a hardcore sim like this. GUNS GUNS GUNS: Ballistics are modeled to be as close to possible as the real thing. This means gravity drop/pattern spreads, ballistic modeling for impact on various things. It's a simulator. That being said...so many people have become 'conditioned' to 'balance/fairness' for multiplayer aspects. IE: In those FPS games they will adjust/nerf/improve guns based on player feedback and perfomance, largly due to map constraints in the sake of 'balance' vs 'realism'. That's not here. It's all just math in a sandbox. To some people, that is great, to others...a nightmare of people screaming "SRAW IS OP!/GUN X IS OP!". Balance and 'fairness' is not why you play a simulation though. Also bear in mind it's quite common to have fire fights on some areas of 500m or more apart on some areas, so again this is where people might not be used to long range tactical combat. Every weapon in ARMA is usefull and you will be more concerned about your SQUAD loadout vs your own. It's not a lone wolf game, and there are not 'stats/unlocks'. How is it VS "fill in the blank?": Think of this in this comparison. DCS-A10C is more akin to the Arma series, vs say BF/COD/Ace Combat. They all share only one common item "War based". Other than that, they are VERY different experiences. Games like BF/COD, you will litterally be pulling the trigger, or dieing within seconds of spawning in, and if you die, the respawn timers are either non existant, or a short few seconds...it's insta action at it's core, as well as those titles having VERY enclosed maps vs scale of Arma maps. Arma, you will be at a base, and it could be 5-45 minutes depending on a wild spectrum on things whether single player or multiplayer. Some people can't handle traveling more than 10 minutes to a target/engagement area before becoming bored, or will rage quit if they get killed instantly by not using cover. There is no 'red flash, retreat to cover'....generally speaking in comparison to FPS's mentioned above. Depends on what you got hit by, and where. 9/10 you're going to be insta killed. This forces VERY tactical cautious team based game play...because who wants another 5-15 minute trip from home base back to the action? I play both DCS, ARMA, and BF series, and they each have their time and place. Comparing them is hard to do as they are truly not the same genre really. The biggest buyer remorse with series like these (ARMA/DCS) is people go into them expecting an 'alternative' to a mainstream BF/COD/Ace Combat play style, only to then find out they stepped into an entirely different genre of game/sim play style. Like others have said....'should you buy it?' If you want a brutal infantry/ground vehichle (primarily infantry) sandbox large scale map simulation with lots of modding options=Absolutley. If you want a harcore 'flight sim': No, buy DCS instead. Flight mechanics here are more simish than BF, but not even close to DSC series. You buy ARMA more so for the infantry combat aspect. If you want an alternative to BF/COD/MOH: Absolutlety not. It's not the same genre of software at all. I know all the screenshots and user videos can make it 'appear so'...but the reality is that it doesn't play like that at all.
Thien_Nguyen;-;One of the best combined arms simulations i have ever played. The gameplay is only hindered by the people and community you play with. Play with an exciting group of people or with friends and you will have all the funny, stupid, and downright awsome moments you can only have in a few combined arms game. However playing by your self is not always boring but not always fun. So what are you waiting for try this game out and if you want find a good clan to hang out with and have fun.
Ze King;-;Very good game. The campaign is a large step up from Arma 2 being both interesting, enjoyable, somewhat challenging and free from annoying AI leaders and teammates. Multiplayer is varied with both casual servers and clan servers with large battles occuring. The maps are both beautiful and varied, it is also a good template for mission makers. The main part of Arma III, however is the mods and missions created by the community, this is what Arma is all about. User created missions vary from single player stealth mission to large battles from land and air, there are even some more creative mission that allow you to become other things like a police officer. BIS have given the community an enjoyable game which doubles up as a template for a large amount of mods and missions both new and old. There are however some problem namely the optimisation. The is very laggy, there is however some solutions and after a bit of tweaking the game should be very playable. Squad management is still time comsuming but after some practice (from the campaign) it does become slightly easier. Overall Arma III is an excellent game and has set out on what it was going to achieve: Become an interesting and enjoyable game while allowing the community to create excellent mods and missions. Dont listen to people complaining about optimisation and content because optimisation can be solved with a google search and content can easily be fleshed out by those who have excellently contributed to the game on things such as the workshop and Armaholic. This game is worth every penny.
