rustie;-;Great game, great mods, great community. This game has so many possibilities I couldn't even give you an estimated guess. The pseudo-realism in this game is absolutely fantastic, and can make for some pretty clever shenanigans when put to the test. With modern graphics, gameplay mechanics, and a hearty helping of (good, although somewhat over-priced) DLC, it definitely has a top spot contender in my book. In single player, the campaign missions are beautifully paced (something which we rarely see in this genre). While playing them, I felt very engaged and felt a very present sense of urgency. This sense of urgency really helps to propel the first chapter, because you feel as if the world around you is slipping away- right as you and your comrades fight to take it back. On top of that, there are some very interesting mechanics and side missions you can do during the campaign, one of which will let you do a sort of "freeroam" mode where you can complete various "user-generated" missions. These missions will pop up out of nowhere, as you are running along on your ATV, deep into enemy territory as you suddenly come upon a military checkpoint with heavy armaments. You can either choose to systematically take the sentries and those pesky LMG carrying grunts, or you can choose to rush right in and take it for mother russia. But you could also just run around it, seeing as how you have an ATV, but alas, how much fun would that be? This game has some of the best gamemodes and user-created mods that I have ever had the pleasure of playing and competing in. With such smash-hit game modes as Wasteland, King of The Hill (just to name a few)- and my personal favorite, Breaking Point, the fun almost never stops. However, I did definitely have the most fun on Breaking Point. A Day-Z esque master piece, with a beautiful blend of PvP and PvE. Battling zombies is not as cumbersome as they may be to a low-gear player in DayZ, and I think it for the better. When you have low level gear, they are just something to avoid as you survey the outskirts of town on the large, 300km map Altis, or the many other maps that the mod offers. While playing with a group on this mod, as well as other game-modes, I have had some of the best online gaming experiences I have ever had. And that's hard to beat. All-in-all, I think that this is a must-have for anybody who loves to play with a group of friends on a saturday night and have fun killing a bunch of noobs military-style!
DatGhilliedGuy;-;Okay so this is my first review. I have played the game for a while now, and i really do enjoy playing, I came in not having really any simulation experience, and this game, well it got me hooked. This game can cater for everyones needs, it hosts a variety of mods to enjoy and much more. I started out buying the game, downloading and got straight into the action i played invade and annex, a mission where you have to complete tasks with a squad you get assigned to. Everyone is normally very friendly and i admitted straight away im new, and got help by a very friendly group of guys and they truly did help. Next i played something that was blowing up at the time, Altis Life, i had one friend, and at the end of 2 or so nights, i left the server with an extra 4 friends who i still am in touch with, Arma 3 is a brilliant game/sim that truly does bring people together. The game itself, is breathtakingly stunning, the graphics are incredible, the physics are good and sometimes just funny. The sounds are immersive and everything forms a package of awesomeness. Obviously like all games there is always going to be bugs, but on this i havent run into many. So from my POV Arma 3 gets a solid 9/10 GG Bohemia
