skywill_15;-;I was really hopeful about ARMA. As it is, it was pretty lame. Maybe it'd be better if I had a super fast computer, AND everyone had the fastest internet known to mankind. It is almost as realistic as WarThunder, but jumpy, jagged, and with laggy multiplayer. Some say the controls are confusing, but I don't agree. The controls are a little different, but you get used to them fairly quickly. Some of the confusion comes from putting more than one action with the same button, switching based on whether it is a tap or a hold. I referenced the controls menu a bunch, but there are numerous tutorials, guides, training scenarios and other practice available right in the game. I really appreciate how realistic it is in that there are no markers for the enemy, and it only takes a couple of hits to kill you. Unfortunately, it always takes at least 4 bullets to kill an enemy. Unless you hit the face. The helmet will not do, you must hit the face or neck. This is actually pretty hard to do when you are at distances of 100+m, which you usually are engaging at those distances +/- 50m, and when they shoot more accurately than you because you have been walking/running everywhere and thus have less fatigue. Avoid ever sprinting, even though the map is bigger than any map in any other game you've ever played in, just be patient and take 2-4 minutes to walk to the next battle. "If you run, you'll just die tired". I went into a multiplayer game and saw helicopters flying around in crazy upside down positions, crashing and falling to the ground. Perhaps a contributing factor was the fact that it was a 70+ person game. When I joined, I saw in the chat room that players were complaining about the lag, as I quickly downloaded a 3.4 MB setting file from the server. Obviously, my joining the game clogged their upstream pipe. This happened a couple times in the game as new players joined, lag spiked. Perhaps a fix of this could be a download mirror used for all servers, or something to save on server bandwidth. This game made me laugh at how unpolished it was at several points. Mostly this was for multiplayer lag jumps, but it was funny when I tried my first multiplayer mission and my trooper, who was not the squad leader, would not stop calling out orders to everyone every 10 seconds. I tried figuring out why I was issuing all these commands, but it happened without my pressing buttons or anything close to the squad command buttons. It was also funny because the in-game voice chat toggle button defaults to [Caps Lock], so when I returned to typing out messages they were SHOUTING HALF THE TIME. Oops. I couldnt figure out how to stop ordering everyone to regroup with me, nor could I find the enemy (it was a co-op mission), so I decided to try something else. In my second multiplayer game, I was starting to get the hang of it. I died plenty at first, sure, but there was always a nice helicopter pilot ready to take us to the battlefield when I respawned. I'm REALLY GLAD I didn't have to walk all that way, because if I did, once would have been enough for me to quit. I was starting to get the hang of it, and even a few kills. Someone finally got me while from a higher building, and I was returning to the battlefield in a helicopter. I started typing to my teammates while riding in the heli, and even though I was typing a message, when I used spacebar during the message, it caused me to jump out of the helicopter without a parachute. I died before I could finish typing out my question, but in a way it answered a different one. I decided to stop playing multiplayer and try the campaign. In the first mission it was funny to have an enemy blazing away full tilt at my essential NPC partner, and for him to not even notice the enemy was there, walking on by. I would have preferred my AI teammate to actually engage the enemy, but I'm sure walking up and shoulder checking him as he walked by was pretty effective. In the same mission, I snuck up on a machine gunner in the same first mission and wanted to see what the "action" button would do when I got close. It turns out, instead of knifing him or doing some other crazy-cool CQB maneuver, I pulled out my medical kit and started bandaging him while he turned his MG on my face and opened up. In the second mission, I wasn't able to progress because one member of my squad spotted an MRAP that he REALLY wanted me to destroy, even when our mission didn't call for it. The rest of our squad was fine to go to the Rendezvous point, but that NPC squad member kept yelling for us to take out the group of enemies by it. The squad leader kept yelling for him to return to formation, and I just kept walking through the forest for a while, hoping that he'd return at the next script line for the story. He didn't. I ended up going back to the last autosave and taking out the rest of them, by myself (after 20+ tries), without backup. I was a little glad I did, because when allies engage the enemy, they die as fast as the enemy does. Which is as fast as you do. Which is QUICK. I never neded up finishing that mission, because even when I knew generally where the enemy was coming from, I couldn't see them to shoot them. But they sure could see and shoot me through all the leaves and bushes in the forest. I died over and over. I'm sure it was a bit like 'Nam, and just as fun. So I decided to uninstall. If it weren't for that, the campaign at least has great production value, on par with Call of Duty. The voice acting, scripting of scenes, and music all are top notch. It is ready for Oculus IR, and maybe I'd enjoy it more if I had a computer that wasn't at least 6 years old. I am usually a simulation enthusiast, loving realism even over gameplay (hey, I like WarThunder, where you also have a hard time identifying who is an enemy and you die in 1-2 hits). However, this was just not very enjoyable. ARMA is like fighting on 3 or 4 battlefield 3 maps at once, with 100 players. That sounds fun, and it could be. As it is, however, it tries to do entirely too much (for my computer). It ends up being a laggy, frustrating mess. It'd be fun at a convention, on a LAN, with computers with monster video cards, because the draw distance is intense. But I was frustrated, not having fun, and ready to uninstall after just a few hours.
