Argyll;-;The game really tries to re-creat combat experience at a platoon level. The interaction with team member is good. However, there are some problems with the game. Enemies usually takes 4 shots to take down. There does not seem to be a difference between a head shot and a shot on the hand. All the enemy ever does when shot is twisting a little. It's rather boring to pull a head shot and still have to land another 3 bullets on the enemy. The shots do not penatrate grass or leaves very well. There is an obvious bug where your aim is snapped to the nearest object when close behind that object. For example, when you stand behind a tree, your aim will be snapped to the trunk. The zoom with the scope is very fake. You look into the scope, yet you see everything in the peripheral also zoomed. So on and so forth. The game needs more work.
ahanmalli;-;The PC Exclusive Title "Arma 3" is a perfect example of a gaming masterpiece. Set in the later 2030s in the fictional island nations of Altis and Stratis. Arma 3 boasts a map a little smaller than twice the size of Washington, D.C.. Arma 3 also has an extraordinarily large and challenging campaign, which I am still struggling to complete. Also, the game is known to be extremely graphically demanding, but I can still run it on my Macbook Pro 13" on low settings on 60fps. Also, Arma 3 boasts a variety of wonderful fictional vehicles ranging from civillian vehicles to army transport. One of the best traits about Arma 3 is the fact that is has so many free mods supported on it, the most popular being Arma 3 Life (Real-Life Roleplaying Mod). The only con for Arma 3 is the demanding price, as a game that costs $60 is pretty expensive. Otherwise, I highly recommend Arma 3 due to it's great contribution to PC Gaming.
